---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Navigation from "../../components/Navigation.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
---

<Layout title="HisabProx Case Study">
  <Navigation />

  <main id="main-content" class="flex-1 max-w-[72ch] mx-auto px-6 py-16 sm:py-24 flex flex-col gap-12 font-sans">
    
    <!-- Header -->
    <header class="flex flex-col gap-4">
      <div class="flex gap-2 text-xs text-[#71717A] font-mono">
        <span>Work</span>
        <span>·</span>
        <span>Case Study</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-display font-medium text-[#FAFAFA] tracking-tight leading-tight">
        HisabProx
      </h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-[#A1A1AA] italic">
        "Build things that still make sense a decade later."
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- Case Study Content -->
    <div class="flex flex-col gap-12 text-[#FAFAFA] text-base leading-[1.7] tracking-tight font-normal">
      
      <!-- Overview -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Overview</h2>
        <p>
          HisabProx helps freelance developers generate and manage client invoices without external database storage.
          The utility focuses on complete client privacy and data ownership.
          It compiles and stores all records locally on the user's machine.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Challenge -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Challenge</h2>
        <p>
          Ensuring client data privacy without hosting expensive cloud database infrastructure.
          Freelancers want to avoid paying recurring fees for simple invoice utilities.
          The solution must remain lightweight, fast, and secure.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Approach -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Approach</h2>
        <p>
          I built a static application that runs completely in the browser sandbox.
          It stores data inside browser local storage and compiles PDFs on the client side.
          The user can export their record dataset as a static JSON file for backups.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Architecture -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Architecture</h2>
        <p>
          The utility is built with TypeScript and React.
          It uses local storage for temporary persistence and PDFKit for client-side PDF generation.
          The application has no backend servers or database integrations.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Trade-offs -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Trade-offs</h2>
        <p>
          I traded multi-device synchronization for complete client privacy and zero maintenance costs.
          Users must manually export backups if they switch computers.
          However, this eliminates data leaks and removes any operating costs.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Outcome -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Outcome</h2>
        <p>
          The application serves as a reliable invoice generator.
          Operating cost is zero dollars, and client data never leaves the user's browser.
          The compiler exports clean, standard PDF invoices instantly.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Lessons -->
      <section class="flex flex-col gap-3">
        <h2 class="text-xs text-[#71717A] uppercase tracking-wider font-semibold">Lessons</h2>
        <p>
          The most secure and cost-effective system is the one that avoids storing data on a remote server.
          Client-side capabilities are often underutilized in modern web development.
          Local-first architectures are ideal for utility tools.
        </p>
      </section>

    </div>

    <!-- Tech Stack footer -->
    <footer class="flex flex-col gap-6 border-t border-[rgba(255,255,255,0.08)] pt-8 mt-4 text-xs font-mono text-[#71717A]">
      <span>Technologies: TypeScript · React · Local Storage · PDFKit</span>
    </footer>

  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
